<!-- e hearst/templates/premium/article/content/gallery.tpl -->	
                </section>
                                                <section class="body">                 	<p>Elly Simmons is in the highly unusual position of being able to say that she started her coronavirus-related fundraiser because Taj Mahal told her to do it.</p>


                                                                	<p>The famous blues musician is a longtime friend of Simmons&rsquo;, who co-owns the 52-year-old bar <a href="https://www.sfchronicle.com/food/article/Specs-bar-cements-its-legacy-in-North-Beach-9193115.php">Specs&rsquo; Twelve Adler Museum Cafe,</a> better known as Specs&rsquo;, in San Francisco&rsquo;s North Beach. Like many bar owners &mdash; <a href="https://www.sfchronicle.com/wine/article/Despite-reported-increase-in-drinking-California-15199995.php">like many business owners,</a> period &mdash; Simmons has been struggling to figure out how to keep her bar alive since shelter-in-place orders forced it to close in March.</p>


                                                                	
                                                                	<p>Her daughter Maralisa Simmons-Cook, who co-owns the bar with her, had started a <a href="https://www.gofundme.com/f/keep-specs-afloat">GoFundMe campaign</a> for $25,000, a fraction of what they actually needed to stay afloat. But Simmons couldn&rsquo;t shake her discomfort with asking for money. Then they saw an encouraging sign: Their neighbor City Lights Bookstore <a href="https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/books/city-lights-coronavirus-fundraiser-collects-more-than-300000-in-one-day">raised more than $300,000</a> on GoFundMe in a single day.</p>


                                                                	<p>&ldquo;When Taj called I happened to be making matzo for Passover,&rdquo; Simmons says. &ldquo;He loves City Lights, and he&rsquo;d always come to our bar afterward.&rdquo; He understands the uniquely quirky charm of Specs&rsquo;, named for its founder Richard &ldquo;Specs&rdquo; Simmons (Elly Simmons&rsquo; father): Its wall-to-wall exhibits of tchotchkes. Its informed-consent cards dispensed by bartenders (&ldquo;Sir, the lady is not interested in your company&rdquo;). Its insistence on being a place where you&rsquo;re not on your phone or your laptop, but where you actually talk to other people.</p>


                                                                	<p>Taj Mahal encouraged Simmons to launch a serious fundraiser, right away. &ldquo;Taj said, &lsquo;You need to do it for the place to survive.&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>


                                                                	<p>And so Simmons and her daughter decided to grit their teeth and ask for more help. They increased the goal to $100,000, a figure closer to what they actually need.</p>


                                                                	
<!-- ferd/premium/article//content/photo.tpl -->
				<section class="media media-photo photo-10857778" data-progressive="true" data-component="photo">
	<img data-src="https://s.hdnux.com/photos/51/32/64/10857778/9/420x0.jpg" data-src-2x="https://s.hdnux.com/photos/51/32/64/10857778/9/640x0.jpg" itemprop="photo" class="fullwidth" alt="Longtime bartender Jacqueline Beier chats in 2016 with a customer at 52-year-old Specs’." /><div class="media-meta"><div class="media-meta-section media-meta-caption"><span class="media-meta-caption-inner">Longtime bartender Jacqueline Beier chats in 2016 with a customer at 52-year-old Specs’.</span><div class="media-meta-credits">Photo: Gabrielle Lurie / Special to The Chronicle 2016</div></div></div>
</section>
<!-- e ferd/premium/article//content/photo.tpl -->



                                                                	<p>Their situation is not unique. Countless Bay Area bars have launched fundraisers since shelter-in-place orders began, including many in North Beach like Vesuvio, Gino &amp; Carlo and Comstock Saloon. Unlike restaurants, which may remain <a href="https://projects.sfchronicle.com/2020/restaurant-delivery/">open for takeout and delivery,</a> bars that don&rsquo;t serve food are left without any options for revenue under the current guidelines. (One longtime North Beach bar and restaurant, Tosca Cafe, surprisingly <a href="https://www.sfchronicle.com/food/article/San-Francisco-s-Tosca-Cafe-reopens-despite-15156624.php">reopened under new ownership</a> during shelter in place, for takeout only.)</p>


                                                                	
                                                                	<p>For all the bars asking for help right now, a lot is at stake: employment, community gathering spaces, independent business ownership. But there&rsquo;s an additional urgency to the predicaments of old bars in North Beach like Vesuvio and Specs&rsquo;, which was among the first in San Francisco to <a href="https://www.sfchronicle.com/food/article/Specs-bar-cements-its-legacy-in-North-Beach-9193115.php">receive &ldquo;legacy business&rdquo; status.</a></p>


                                                                	<p>Their stretch of Columbus Avenue is one of the most distinctive parts of the city, transporting visitors to bygone eras of San Francisco&rsquo;s past &mdash; the clandestine Barbary Coast, the romantic Beats. And yet, even before the coronavirus crisis, many of these landmark tourist destinations were struggling.</p>


                                                                	<p>&ldquo;Not as many people stay out until 2 a.m. as (they) used to,&rdquo; Simmons says.</p>


                                                                	<!-- ferd/hearst/templates/premium/article/content/related-links.tpl -->
