s to make money during...</h4></div></a></div></li><li class="relatedStories--item noImage" data-number="4"><div class="card" data-number="4"><a class="hdn-analytics" href="https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/books/city-lights-coronavirus-fundraiser-collects-more-than-300000-in-one-day" data-hdn-analytics="related_stories|link-98432|article-15205341|4"><div class="card--headline"><h4 class="card--headline-title">city-lights-coronavirus-fundraiser-collects-more-than-300000-i...</h4></div></a></div></li><li class="relatedStories--item" data-number="5" data-progressive="true" data-component="photo"><div class="card" data-number="5"><a class="hdn-analytics" href="https://www.sfchronicle.com/wine/article/Longtime-bartenders-save-84-year-old-dive-bar-15045831.php" data-hdn-analytics="related_stories|article-15045831|article-15205341|5"><div class="card--image"><img data-src='https://s.hdnux.com/photos/01/10/41/07/19010009/7/gallery_medium.jpg'></div><div class="card--headline"><h6 class="card--retSection">Wine & Spirits</h6><h6 class="card--headline-byline">By Peter Lawrence Kane</h6><h4 class="card--headline-title">Longtime bartenders save 84-year-old dive bar Columbus Cafe in...</h4></div></a></div></li>
		</ul>
	</section>
<!-- e ferd/hearst/templates/premium/article/content/related-links.tpl -->
                                                                	<p>Even after laying off their seven employees, who are unionized, since the crisis started, Simmons and Simmons-Cook still had to pay rent, taxes, licensing fees and employee health coverage, among other costs. According to their bookkeeper, Simmons says, $100,000 was a low estimate.</p>


                                                                	<p>The co-owners considered taking out a bank loan or bringing on a silent partner, but ultimately decided against taking on more debt. &ldquo;It would really be a huge shame to see the bar close, but it would be too risky to put ourselves in that financial position,&rdquo; Simmons-Cook says.</p>


                                                                	
                                                                	<p>So far, they&rsquo;ve raised more than $47,000 from more than 800 donors.</p>


                                                                	<p>The current proliferation of GoFundMe campaigns for small businesses says something about the way that these business owners perceive the availability of government assistance. &ldquo;The government response is so anemic,&rdquo; says Janet Clyde, co-owner of the 72-year-old bar Vesuvio, which has a GoFundMe page to raise money for its employees&rsquo; living expenses. &ldquo;It pits large, sophisticated entities against small, less sophisticated people,&rdquo; she says, referring to the first-come, first-served nature of the <a href="https://www.sfchronicle.com/business/article/Bay-Area-small-businesses-How-to-get-coronavirus-15178270.php">Economic Injury Disaster Loans,</a> among other problems. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s not serving us well.&rdquo;</p>


                                                                	<p>In fact, the White House announced Thursday that its other economic program for small businesses during the crisis, the $350 billion Paycheck Protection Program, <a href="https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Coronavirus-live-updates-news-bay-area-15192855.php">had run out of money.</a></p>


                                                                	
<!-- ferd/premium/article//content/photo.tpl -->
				<section class="media media-photo photo-16962761" data-progressive="true" data-component="photo">
	<img data-src="https://s.hdnux.com/photos/01/00/55/23/16962761/7/420x0.jpg" data-src-2x="https://s.hdnux.com/photos/01/00/55/23/16962761/7/640x0.jpg" itemprop="photo" class="fullwidth" alt="Hugh Linn (left) enjoys a drink at Vesuvio Cafe." /><div class="media-meta"><div class="media-meta-section media-meta-caption"><span class="media-meta-caption-inner">Hugh Linn (left) enjoys a drink at Vesuvio Cafe.</span><div class="media-meta-credits">Photo: Michael Macor / The Chronicle 2017</div></div></div>
</section>
<!-- e ferd/premium/article//content/photo.tpl -->



                                                                	<p>Clyde began working at Vesuvio in 1979 &mdash; &ldquo;I was the morning bartender, working 6 a.m. to 10 a.m.,&rdquo; she says &mdash; and she and her family gradually became co-owners of the bar with the Fein family. They own their building, which puts them in a different financial position from renters like Simmons and Simmons-Cook. For now, Clyde says they&rsquo;re not asking for any help with their own expenses, just for the employees&rsquo;.</p>


                                                                	<p>The business owners of North Beach share an uncommon camaraderie. &ldquo;Vesuvio, the Beat Museum, Trieste &mdash; all of us are from the same era and we all share the same customers,&rdquo; says Simmons-Cook, referring to the 64-year-old espresso bar Caffe Trieste. &ldquo;We all need each other to survive.&rdquo;</p>


                                                                	
                                                                	<p>Specs met his wife, Sonia, while bartending at Vesuvio. A few years later, he opened his own bar across the street. (Specs, so named for the spectacles he wore, <a href="https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Richard-Specs-Simmons-popular-owner-of-9967709.php">died in 2016.)</a> The two bars look quite different &mdash; Vesuvio with its stained glass and mezzanine, Specs&rsquo; with its busy exhibit walls &mdash; but are alike in friendliness, and both feel like a time capsule to a different time. Vesuvio was frequented by poet Jack Kerouac; Specs&rsquo;, which came around 20 years later, by <a href="https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/music/singer-songwriter-john-prine-has-died-at-73-due-to-the-coronavirus">recently deceased folk singer John Prine,</a> according to Simmons. And, of course, Taj Mahal.</p>


                                                                	<p>If social-distancing measures remain in place for much longer, will these bars and their neighbors survive? For now, it&rsquo;s hard to know, says Clyde. &ldquo;If we reopen, we can make it,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;As long as we can reopen in some shape or form.</p>


                                                                	<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s not just about selling drinks,&rdquo; Simmons says.</p>


                                                                	<p>&ldquo;Specs opened the bar because he had a really deep love of humanity,&rdquo; she says.  &ldquo;What bars are really about is the people and the stories and connection.&rdquo;</p>


                                                                	<em><p>Esther Mobley is The San Francisco Chronicle&rsquo;s wine critic. Email: <a href="mailto:emobley@sfchronicle.com">emobley@sfchronicle.com</a> Twitter: <a href="https://twitter.com/Esther_mobley">@Esther_mobley</a> Instagram: <a href="https://twitter.com/esthermob">@esthermob</a></p></em>


                            </section>
        <footer class="footer">
